items.content_latex:
Science relies on experimental evidence. Mathematics relies on logic and reasoning.

A \textbf{mathematical proof} is a correct argument which establishes the truth of a mathematical statement.

A mathematical proof:
\begin{itemize}
\item starts with assumptions called \textbf{hypotheses}
\item is a sequence of correct mathematical steps
\item ends in a \textbf{conclusion}
\end{itemize}

A group of people are involved in a business meeting. Alice looks at Bob and Bob looks at Clare. Alice is married but Clare is not.

\textbf{Things to think about:}
\begin{enumerate}
\item[a] Do we know whether Bob is married?
\item[b] Can we \textit{prove} that a married person looks at an unmarried person?
\item[c] What is necessary for a mathematical argument to be convincing and complete?
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Proof:}

Bob is either married or he is not married.
\begin{itemize}
\item If Bob is married, then when Bob looks at Clare, a married person looks at an unmarried person.
\item If Bob is \textit{not} married, then when Alice looks at Bob, a married person looks at an unmarried person.
\end{itemize}

In both cases, a married person looks at an unmarried person.

These cases exhaust all possibilities, so a married person always looks at an unmarried person.

questions.problem_latex:
For each statement, state its negation:
\begin{enumerate}
\item[a] The cat is black.
\item[b] $x$ is prime.
\item[c] The tree is deciduous.
\end{enumerate}

State, with justification, whether each statement is true or false:
\begin{enumerate}
\item[a] If $n^2 > 9$ then $n > 3$.
\item[b] If $x > 3$ then $x^2 > 9$.
\item[c] $x = 3$ if and only if $x^2 = 9$.
\end{enumerate}

State, with justification, whether each statement is true or false:
\begin{enumerate}
\item[a] If $x$ is positive then $\sqrt{x} \in \mathbb{R}$.
\item[b] If $\sqrt{x} \in \mathbb{R}$, then $x$ is positive.
\item[c] $x$ is positive if and only if $\sqrt{x} \in \mathbb{R}$.
\end{enumerate}

Determine whether $A$ and $B$ are equivalent:
\begin{enumerate}
\item[a] $A$: $xy = 0$. $B$: $(x = 0) \vee (y = 0)$ $(x = 0)$
\item[b] $A$: $x$ is even. $B$: $x^2$ is even.
\end{enumerate}

There are four cards on a table. Every card has a letter set on one side and a number on the other. With the cards placed, you see:
\begin{center}
D \quad 3 \quad K \quad 7
\end{center}
Identify precisely which cards you need to turn over, and which you do not, to establish the truth of the statement: ``Every card which has a D on one side has a 7 on the other''. (This problem was studied in 1966 by Peter Wason.)

items.content_latex:
\textbf{Example 1}

\textbf{a} Prove by deduction: ``If $x < -5$ then $x^2 > 25$.''
\textbf{b} Explain why the converse is \textit{not} true.

questions.answer_latex:
If $x < -5$ then $|x| > 5$ \quad \{geometric definition of absolute value\}
$\therefore |x|^2 > 5^2$ \quad \{squaring both sides\}
$\therefore x^2 > 25$ \quad \{$|x|^2 = x^2$\}

items.content_latex:
To maintain mathematical equivalence, we can:
\begin{itemize}
\item add or subtract the same term from both sides of an equation
\item multiply or divide both sides of an equation by a non-zero term
\item substitute for an equivalent sub-term, for example by replacing a term by its factored or expanded form.
\end{itemize}

In a \textbf{direct proof} we start with the hypothesis and work forward to the conclusion.

For example, here is a direct proof that if $a < b$ then $a < \frac{a+b}{2}$.

\textbf{Proof:}
$a < b$
$\Rightarrow 2a < a + b$ \quad \{dividing by 2 which is $> 0$\}
$\Rightarrow a < \frac{a+b}{2}$ \quad \{adding $a$ to both sides\}

In \textbf{proof by contradiction} we deliberately assume the opposite to what we are trying to prove. By a series of correct steps we show that this is impossible, hence our assumption must be false, and so its opposite is true. We call this an \textbf{indirect proof} because we do not start with the hypothesis.

For example, here is a proof by contradiction that if $a < b$ then $a < \frac{a+b}{2}$.

\textbf{Proof (by contradiction):}
For $a < b$, suppose that $a \geqslant \frac{a+b}{2}$.
$\Rightarrow 2a \geqslant a + b$ \quad \{multiplying both sides by 2\}
$\Rightarrow 2a - a \geqslant b$ \quad \{subtracting $a$ from both sides\}
This is a contradiction to our assumption, so the supposition must be false and the alternative, $a < \frac{a+b}{2}$, must be true.

In mathematics we clearly \textit{define} terms so there is no misunderstanding of their exact meaning.

For example:
\begin{itemize}
\item A \textbf{rational number} is a number which can be written in the form $\frac{p}{q}$ where $p, q \in \mathbb{Z}$, $q \neq 0$.
\item An \textbf{integer} is even if $n = 2k$ for some integer $k$.
\item An \textbf{integer} is odd if $n = 2k + 1$ for some integer $k$.
\end{itemize}

We can understand the need for specific definitions by considering integers and rational numbers:
\begin{itemize}
\item 2 is an integer, and is also a rational number since $2 = \frac{2}{1}$.
\item $\frac{1}{2}$ is a rational number, and is also an integer since $\frac{1}{2} = \frac{2}{4}$.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Discussion questions:}
\begin{enumerate}
\item Why is it important that mathematicians use the same definitions?
\item Words such as \textit{similar}, or \textit{function}, \textit{domain}, \textit{range}, and \textit{wave} are common words in English, but also have different or more specific mathematical definitions. For each of these words, discuss the difference between their mathematical definition and their common use in English.
\item What is the difference between \textit{equal}, \textit{equivalence}, and \textit{the same}? Why is it important to distinguish between these terms?
\item Are there any words which we use only in mathematics? What does this tell us about the nature of mathematics and the world around us?
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Proof:}
$0 = 0 + 0$
$\therefore 0 \times x = (0 + 0) \times x$ \quad \{multiplying both sides by $x$\}
$\therefore 0 \times x = 0 \times x + 0 \times x$ \quad \{Axiom 3\}
$\therefore 0 \times x + (-(0 \times x)) = (0 \times x + 0 \times x) + (-(0 \times x))$ \quad \{adding the additive inverse of $0 \times x$\}
$\therefore 0 \times x + (-(0 \times x)) = (0 \times x) + [0 \times x + (-(0 \times x))]$ \quad \{Axiom 1\}
$\therefore 0 = 0 \times x + 0$
$\therefore 0 = 0 \times x$ \quad \{Axiom 4\}
$\therefore 0 \times x = 0 = x \times 0$ \quad \{Axiom 2\}

A proof can sometimes be split into a finite number of cases, each of which is then proven separately. It is important to justify why the list of cases covers \textit{all} possible cases. Since the list \textit{exhausts} all possibilities, we call this style of proof a \textbf{proof by exhaustion}.

For example, every natural number $n \in \mathbb{Z}$ is either even or odd.
\begin{itemize}
\item If $n$ is even it is divisible by two, and so $n = 2k$ for some $k \in \mathbb{Z}$.
\item If $n$ is odd, it has remainder 1 when divided by 2. In this case $n = 2k + 1$ for some $k \in \mathbb{Z}$.
\end{itemize}

questions.problem_latex:
You are presented with 3 boxes, A, B, and C, one of which contains a prize. On the lid of each box there is a statement, and you are told that only one of the statements is true. They say:
\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|}
\hline
A & B & C \\
\hline
The prize is in this box. & The prize is not in this box. & The prize is in box A. \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
Which box contains the prize?
